0.9966397285461426, "span": {"begin": 1074, "end": 1083}}, {"id": ["mesh:D004967"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "estrogen", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9995871186256409, "span": {"begin": 1133, "end": 1141}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:1588"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "ovarian aromatase", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.995118260383606, "span": {"begin": 1154, "end": 1171}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:5351"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "luteinizing hormone", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9959735870361328, "span": {"begin": 1344, "end": 1363}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:1588"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "CYP19", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9943245649337769, "span": {"begin": 1423, "end": 1428}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:1588"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "aromatase", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9838545918464661, "span": {"begin": 1438, "end": 1447}}, {"id": ["NCBITaxon:9606"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "humans", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.9914381504058838, "span": {"begin": 1451, "end": 1457}}, {"id": ["mesh:D004967"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "estrogen", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9971851706504822, "span": {"begin": 1544, "end": 1552}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:1588"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "aromatase gene", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9925636053085327, "span": {"begin": 1652, "end": 1666}}, {"id": ["NCBITaxon:9606"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "human", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.9816438555717468, "span": {"begin": 1725, "end": 1730}}, {"id": ["mesh:D004700"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "estrogen-dependent diseases", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.99689120054245, "span": {"begin": 1731, "end": 1758}}, {"id": ["mesh:D004967"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "estrogen", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9995681643486023, "span": {"begin": 1731, "end": 1739}}, {"id": ["mim:114480", "mesh:D001943"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "breast cancer", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9999898672103882, "span": {"begin": 1770, "end": 1783}}, {"id": ["mim:608089", "mesh:D016889"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "endometrial cancer", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.999997615814209, "span": {"begin": 1785, "end": 1803}}, {"id": ["mim:131200", "mesh:D004715"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "endometriosis", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9999980926513672, "span": {"begin": 1809, "end": 1822}}], "text": "Biological state  Aromatase (Cyp19a1, estrogen synthetase, estrogen synthase) is an enzyme responsible for a key step in the biosynthesis of estrogens, in particular it is responsible for conversion of C-19 androgens into C-18 estrogens (E R Simpson et al., 1994), (Ryan, 1982). It is a member of the cytochrome P450 superfamily (Ryan, 1982). The aromatase gene uses multiple promoters in a tissue-specific manner, resulting in a tissue-specific regulation of aromatase activity (Evan R Simpson, 2004). The cAMP/PKA/CREB pathway is considered to be the primary signalling cascade through which the gonadal Cyp19 promoter is regulated (Stocco, 2008).  Biological compartments  Aromatase in the specialized cells of the ovary, hypothalamus, and placenta has a crucial role in reproduction for mammalian and other vertebrates by converting androgens to estrogens. This enzyme is also present in various other tissues, such as skin, fat, bone marrow, liver, adrenals, and testes (Ryan, 1982).  General role in biology  The ovarian aromatase produces systemic and locally acting estrogens for general reproductive functions. The systemic estrogen produced by ovarian aromatase modulates the central nervous system and pituitary functions for the ovarian cycle and in spontaneously ovulating mammals it triggers the release of the ovulatory surge of luteinizing hormone (Ryan, 1982), (Hillier, 1985). Because only a single gene (CYP19) encodes aromatase in humans, targeted disruption of this gene or inhibition of its product effectively eliminates estrogen biosynthesis (Evan R Simpson et al., 2002). Much attention has been given to the regulation of the aromatase gene and its implication in the development and progression of human estrogen-dependent diseases, including breast cancer, endometrial cancer, and endometriosis, see review (Bulun et al., 2005).", "timestamp": "Fri May 15 21:25:50 +0000 2026"}